<br>
1.  We are a melee class.  Well, kinda.  But actually, up through about 15th level or so, we are still able to stand up front with the 'true' tanks and dish out the damage.  And even later, if played well (i.e., not building up too much agro by singing the wrong songs) and with appropriate equipment, we can still stand in the front lines and hold our own.  We can dual-wield (at 17), wear plate armor (and doesn't Lambent look MAHVELOUS! ) and can use a variety of decent weapons.<br>
<br>
2.  We reduce downtime.  Some would say that's Job #1 for a bard.  From about 6th level on, when we get Hymn of Restoration, we can help the party get back into the fray more quickly.  No, it's not Greater Healing, but it's 9 HP per pulse per party member... that adds up to quite a bit of healing power between fights, and can take a bit of the edge off during battle (though it's a high-taunt song to sing during a fight).  Through in the first mana song at 20, the second at 32 and Cantata of Soothing (HP, mana and stamina restoration) at 34 - not to mention the even more potent songs we get later - and we can keep the groups rocking right along.<br>
<br>
3.  We are... whatever the group needs.  Bards are the swiss army knife, the duct tape of Norrath. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   I was first exposed to this concept in the great guides &quot;Mid-20 Bard Strategies&quot; and &quot;Bards in Combat&quot;, both found at the Concert Hall site (www.attcanada.net/~reaper).  Need to maximize your own damage output?  Chords of Dissonance, Disruptive Discord (both AE DoT songs) and Psalm of Warmth.  Want to buff your tanks while debuffing the monster?  No problem.  Going after casters?  Equip your drum and crank up the Rhythms series.  Crowd control?  Mez, charm, lull before pulling.  You name it, we have a song that can do it (well, almost).  Need to tank for the group?  No problem, keep the agro up with the proper songs and hack away.  Be the puller?  No sweat, Lull and Selo's and Bellow fit the bill.<br>
<br>
4.  We can solo.  I first discovered Bellow kiting after a bad pull on Erud's Crossing.  Nowhere to zone, no guards, just run around the island on Selo's and bellow the zombies to death one by one.  Fear/chain kiting (snare the monster with Consonant Chain, hit'em with fear, the hack'em from behind) opens up at 26th.  Charm kiting (charm one, sic him on his buddy) comes a level later.  Get beat up a bit in the process?  Find a corner, equip your mandolin, and play Hymn of Restoration.<br>
<br>
The real key is knowing the situation, both what you're facing and what your party brings to the table.  Know your songs and adjust your mix accordingly.<br>
<br>
As for what to sing when... more on that later. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
